I am excited to announce that we are advertising a summer school in model-based multivariate analysis for ecologists.
The summer school is intended for PhD students, advanced master students, or researchers that want to analyse (multivariate) data on ecological communities with state-of-the-art statistical models. Such models have great benefits for inference, prediction, and validation, especially compared to more classical methods for multivariate analysis (e.g., DCA, NMDS and such). The covered approaches will include multispecies (vector) generalised linear models and mixed-effects models, model-based ordination, and Joint Species Distribution Models. There will be both lectures and practical R-exercises, and some leisure time to enjoy the beautiful scenery of Dovrefjell national park. We will focus on fitting models with the gllvm R-package<https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/gllvm/index.html> , but will additionally provide an overview of other packages available for fitting similar models, and their pros and cons. There is limited space at the venue, so that a maximum of 23 participants will be admitted. Note that room sharing is to be expected.
Location: Basecamp Frich's Hjerkinn, Hjerkinn, Norway
Application deadline: 3 March
Dates: 21 - 25 July
For information, please contact bert.v.d.veen at ntnu.no<mailto:bert.v.d.veen at ntnu.no>.
More information, including background of the methods and information on the lecturers, a preliminary schedule, and the application form can be found at https://bertv.folk.ntnu.no/index.html.
The summer school is made possible thanks to funding provided by Nordic Society Oikos.



